snippet.textDisplay:
2020 is the last year of our current decade. 2021 will start the new decade. Here's why......

Anno Domini

Anno domini, the year numbering system (calendar era) we use today, was devised by a 6th-century monk named Dionysius Exiguus, who lived in an area now part of Romania and Bulgaria. Dionysius used Roman numerals to number the years “since the incarnation of our Lord Jesus Christ”, as he put it in his writings—and THERE IS NO ROMAN NUMERAL FOR THE NUMBER ZERO. (In fact, it is believed that the concept of the number zero, as it is used today, did not exist in Europe until the 13th century.)

Year 1 BCE Was Followed by Year CE 1
This means that year AD 1 directly followed year 1 BC, without the year count ever reaching zero. In other words, the first year of the anno domini era was year 1, not year 0. As a consequence,

1 full year had passed at the end of year 1;
2 years had passed at the end of year 2;
and so on...

The first decade ended at year 10 and the second decade began with year 11.

At the end of year 1999, as people were celebrating the new millennium, only 1999 full years had passed since the beginning of the calendar era—which is one year short of two full millennia.

2020 does not start a new decade. It marks the beginning of the 20's, but is the last year of our current decade.

Dionysius used Roman numerals to number the years “since the incarnation of our Lord Jesus Christ”, as he put it in his writings—and THERE IS NO ROMAN NUMERAL FOR THE NUMBER ZERO. (In fact, it is believed that the concept of the number zero, as it is used today, did not exist in Europe until the 13th century.)

Year 1 BCE Was Followed by Year CE 1
This means that year AD 1 directly followed year 1 BC, without the year count ever reaching zero. In other words, the first year of the anno domini era was year 1, not year 0. As a consequence,

1 full year had passed at the end of year 1;
2 years had passed at the end of year 2;
and so on...

The first decade ended at year 10 and the second decade began with year 11.

At the end of year 1999, as people were celebrating the new millennium, only 1999 full years had passed since the beginning of the calendar era—which is one year short of two full millennia.

snippet.textDisplay:
Marvel Studios: Is making a Spider-Man movie with the money of Sony under the creative control of Sony
MatPat: Disney did nothing and just grabbed the money.
What?
I don't know what your sources are, but mine differ from yours in many places. (As a Spider-Fan I had a very stressful month until drunken Tom Holland called Bob Iger and begged him to make a new Spider-Man deal ^^')
To prevent this from happening again: yes Disney should buy Spider-Man for 50 trillion. But I'm afraid I would miss the creative influence of Sony. Even if it results in annoying contracting problems and more "maybe people will watch it because they think it's part of the MCU"-movies like Venom, it assures a constant flow of Spider-Man movies (since 2016 we got Spidey in a Movie every Year while e.g. Doctor Strange has years to wait for a reappearence), a consistent musical Spider-Theme by Giacchino and is routing him with forced crossovers inside the MCU because Sony can't stop shouting: YES! HE REALLY IS IN THE MCU! WATCH OUR MOVIES!

Aside of that: I should've closed the video after you roasted Rise of Skywalker just for the sake of roasting Rise of Skywalker 'cause it's cool to roast Rise of Skywalker. I remember a tiime, where star wars fans celebrated bad reviews, because frick critics, what do they know about star wars?
But I guess that is why creators are called influencers these days... A bunch of people, who control their followers with opinions because everyone is to afraid and to lazy to have their own.

snippet.textDisplay:
The one thing is that Disney loves to play it safe, so if Disney has every single right to Spider-Man then the movies wont have risks anymore. No more "I'm gonna put some dirt in your eye." no more stuff like Emo Spider-Man no more savage Bully Maguire. basically the things that are funny but not too funny*, and villains that are good *but not too good
You don't see many Joker or Bane levels of villain with Dinsey



plus all things considered the only reason why people wanted Spidey in the MCU is for the Iron Dad, Spider-Son relationship. But Tony is dead so we dont get that anymore. and Tom Holland, which has a 6 film contract not including Civil War.




If it came down to it, I'd rather see Sony win the custody battle and keep making Spider-Man movies. Movies like: Tobey Maguire Spider-Man, Andrew Garfield Spider-Man, and Into the Spiderverse. All we need is for Sony to keep the film rights and Tom Holland to act for them and all is good.


Either that or Disney can stop being greedy and let Sony share the Spider boi.

snippet.textDisplay:
The math on how much the companies makes is off. The last Spiderman movie might have cost $160,00 to produce and total box office was $1.132 billion, but MatPat didnt take into account the movie theaters cut and marketing expenses. The typical rule of thumb is Movie theaters keep almost 1/3 of what a movie makes, bring the total the film company makes on this to something more like $755 profit. Now Marketing for a big movie like this is also almost as much as the production cost. They spent like $100 million on just that! so take $100 mil off and now its $655 million. Take out the production costs and they make about $500 million. Its not over $1 billion made, its less than half that.


Another thing not mentioned was in the deal the stand alone Spiderman movies are Sony movies, Paid for and distributed by them, but they are still Disney productions. This means Sony paid Disney to make the movies like they would any other production company (Like when you see Bad Robot as producers of a movie or something). So even on Sony only movies, Disney got the Merch $$$ and were paid to make the movies for Sony.


Just some Info on it in case anyone wanted to know!

snippet.textDisplay:
The numbers in the 7 minute segment are wrong... If a movie ticket is $10, Sony might take home $5, not $9.50. The rest go to the Theater.

Sony might earn $395 million off of Spider-Man Homecoming. Meanwhile, Disney earns $44 million + hundreds of millions off merchandise, while Sony only gets $230 million after taking into account the cost to make the film, and then you can subtract the cost of marketing and distribution which is usually in the hundred million margin. By the end, Sony might earn 10-15% of the gross while Disney has 5% plus merchandise.
